LB1135 LB1135
2026 2026
LEGISLATURE OF NEBRASKA
ONE HUNDRED NINTH LEGISLATURE
SECOND SESSION
LEGISLATIVE BILL 1135
FINAL READING
Introduced by Urban Affairs Committee: McKinney, 11, Chairperson;
Cavanaugh, J., 9; Quick, 35; Rountree, 3.
Read first time January 20, 2026
Committee: Urban Affairs
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT relating to government; to amend sections 13-3206,
2 18-2124, 18-2125, 18-2136, 18-3404, 18-3405, 18-3407, 18-3408,
3 18-3410, and 18-3413, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, section
4 18-2117.01, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement, 2024, and
5 sections 18-2101.02 and 18-2147, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025;
6 to adopt the Service Contract Reporting Act; to authorize certain
7 municipal contracts and agreements relating to parking facilities;
8 to change provisions relating to delinquent annual assessments and
9 PACE liens under the Property Assessed Clean Energy Act; to
10 authorize the issuance of conduit revenue bonds and certain taxpayer
11 agreements under the Community Development Law; to change provisions
12 of the Nebraska Municipal Land Bank Act; to provide for the sale of
13 certain waterworks, sewer systems, and water systems to Indian
14 tribes; to harmonize provisions; to provide a duty for the Revisor
15 of Statutes; to provide operative dates; to repeal the original
16 sections; and to declare an emergency.
17 Be it enacted by the people of the State of Nebraska,
-1-

LB1135 LB1135
2026 2026
1 Section 1. Sections 1 to 5 of this act shall be known and may be
2 cited as the Service Contract Reporting Act.
3 Sec. 2. For purposes of the Service Contract Reporting Act:
4 (1) City means a city of the metropolitan class;
5 (2) County means a county in this state with a population of more
6 than five hundred thousand inhabitants as determined by the most recent
7 federal decennial census;
8 (3) Division means the materiel division of the Department of
9 Administrative Services;
10 (4) Fiscal year means the twelve-month period used by the city,
11 county, or state agency for budgeting purposes;
12 (5) Service contract means a contract that:
13 (a) Is awarded by a city, county, or state agency for the provision
14 of legal services, accounting services, financial consulting services,
15 management consulting services, health care services, engineering
16 services, architectural services, information technology services,
17 marketing and advertising services, human resources consulting services,
18 environmental consulting services, educational and training services,
19 snow removal and hauling services, janitorial services, custodial and
20 cleaning services, yard maintenance services, or tree removal services;
21 and
22 (b) Has a value of:
23 (i) For contracts entered into prior to January 1, 2029, seventy
24 thousand dollars or more;
25 (ii) For contracts entered into on or after January 1, 2029, and
26 prior to January 1, 2034, ninety thousand dollars or more; or
27 (iii) For contracts entered into on or after January 1, 2034, one
28 hundred ten thousand dollars or more;
29 (6) State agency means any agency, board, or commission of this
30 state other than the University of Nebraska, the Nebraska state colleges,
31 the courts, the Legislature, or any officer or state agency established
-2-

LB1135 LB1135
2026 2026
1 by the Constitution of Nebraska;
2 (7) State aid means:
3 (a) For both cities and counties, state aid paid pursuant to
4 sections 60-3,202 and 77-3523;
5 (b) For cities, state aid to cities paid pursuant to sections
6 39-2501 to 39-2520, 60-3,190, and 77-27,139.04 and insurance premium tax
7 paid to cities; and
8 (c) For counties, state aid to counties paid pursuant to sections
9 60-3,184 to 60-3,190, insurance premium tax paid to counties, and
10 reimbursements to counties from funds appropriated pursuant to section
11 29-3933; and
12 (8) Zip code means the numerical code used by the United States
13 Postal Service to identify geographic areas.
14 Sec. 3. On or before March 1, 2028, and on or before March 1 of
15 each year thereafter, each city, county, and state agency shall submit a
16 report to the division containing the following information:
17 (1) The name and address of each individual or entity that was
18 awarded a service contract during the most recently completed fiscal year
19 and the type of service involved in each such contract;
20 (2) The total dollar value of service contracts awarded during the
21 most recently completed fiscal year, including an overall total and a
22 breakdown by zip code; and
23 (3) A description of any efforts made by the city, county, or state
24 agency to increase the number of service contracts awarded to individuals
25 and entities located within zip codes with the lowest amounts of service
26 contract awards.
27 Sec. 4. On or before April 1, 2028, and on or before April 1 of
28 each year thereafter, the division shall compile the information reported
29 under section 3 of this act and shall electronically submit a
30 comprehensive report regarding such information to the Governor, the
31 Clerk of the Legislature, and the Urban Affairs Committee of the
-3-

LB1135 LB1135
2026 2026
1 Legislature. The division shall also make the comprehensive report
2 available on the website of the Department of Administrative Services.
3 Sec. 5. If any city or county fails to submit an annual report to
4 the division as required under section 3 of this act, the division shall
5 send notification of the noncompliance to the governing body of the
6 relevant city or county and to the State Treasurer. The State Treasurer
7 shall then suspend all distributions of state aid allocated to the city
8 or county until the annual report is submitted. Once the annual report
9 has been submitted, the city or county shall again become entitled to all
10 distributions of state aid, including any suspended distributions.
11 Sec. 6. (1) Any city of the first class, city of the second class,
12 or village may enter into contracts or agreements with any person, firm,
13 corporation, or political subdivision for the operation, maintenance,
14 management, or enforcement of municipal parking facilities, including
15 onstreet metered parking and offstreet public lots or garages.
16 (2) Such contracts or agreements may authorize the person, firm,
17 corporation, or political subdivision to issue and process parking
18 citations, collect fines, maintain equipment, or operate payment systems,
19 provided that the city or village retains final authority over
20 adjudication and appeals.
21 (3) The city or village shall retain sufficient control over the
22 parking facilities to ensure proper operation in the public interest and
23 to establish or approve all rates, charges, and fines.
24 (4) No contract or agreement under this section shall exceed:
25 (a) Thirty years in duration, including renewals, for a city of the
26 first class; or
27 (b) Ten years in duration, including renewals, for a city of the
28 second class or village.
29 Sec. 7. Section 13-3206, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
30 amended to read:
31 13-3206 (1)(a) For qualifying property other than single-family
